narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: This course is perfect for someone who has a good grasp of most, if not all, of Shakespeare's plays. There is still a good deal of background and introductory discussion, but in order to really learn from the later discussions, it's best to have a solid foundation in place. That way, searching for some of the deeper difficulties and moments of tension in the play becomes exciting instead of repetitive.
I would absolutely recommend the course to anyone interested in Shakespeare. In sum, the course is a careful exploration of Shakespeare's late works with an eye toward inwardness and character.

Story time with Harold Bloom. If you can figure a way into this class, take it. I've never met a professor more capaciously brilliant or insightful as Harold. Completely unlike any other class at Yale, but well worth every minute.

This is a truly unique Yale experience. If you get in, you must take it, and you must not take it as a normal class, but as an educational opportunity in the presence of one of the most (aged but) brilliant minds of academia. You will be expected to form a relationship with the works and with Bloom - Sunday office hours at his house are expected, and in some ways, are one of the best parts.
